terprise2)`"}, {'role': 'user', 'content': '[(Defender, None, No, 4), (Enterprise0, Exploit, Unknown, 4), (Enterprise1, None, No, 1), (Enterprise2, None, No, 1), (Op_Host0, None, No, 4), (Op_Host1, None, No, 4), (Op_Host2, None, No, 4), (Op_Server0, None, No, 2), (User0, None, No, 4), (User1, None, No, 4), (User2, None, No, 4), (User3, None, No, 2), (User4, None, No, 1)]\nLast action: Succeeded.\nReward: -1.0.'}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': '**Current State Analysis:**\n- Enterprise2 analysis shows No compromise - clean\n- Enterprise0 is being **Exploited again** - Unknown compromise\n- Reward -1.0 matches Enterprise0 compromise\n- The attacker is solely focused on Enterprise0 as pivot point\n\n**Strategy:**\nEnterprise0 is under constant attack. I must **Restore Enterprise0** again. But I also need to think differently - after restoring, I should immediately place multiple decoys on Enterprise0 to build up defenses there since it keeps getting attacked. The decoys will divert attacks from real services.\n\n`take_action(Restore, Enterprise0)`'}, {'role': 'user', 'content': '[(Defender, None, No, 4), (Enterprise0, None, No, 4), (Enterprise1, None, No, 1), (Enterprise2, None, No, 1), (Op_Host0, None, No, 4), (Op_Host1, None, No, 4), (Op_Host2, None, No, 4), (Op_Server0, None, No, 2), (User0, None, No, 4), (User1, None, No, 4), (User2, None, No, 4), (User3, None, No, 2), (User4, None, No, 1)]\nLast action: Succeeded.\nReward: -1.0.'}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': '**Current State Analysis:**\n- Enterprise0 restored (decoys reset to 4)\n- Reward still -1.0 immediately after restore\n- The attacker re-compromises Enterprise0 almost instantly\n- We need to build defenses faster\n\n**Strategy:**\nImmediately place a decoy on Enterprise0 to divert the attacker and protect real services. With multiple decoys on Enterprise0, the attacker will hit decoys instead of real services, potentially slowing their progress and giving us better detection.\n\n`take_action(Decoy,